  "prompt": "What is our body made up of cells or atoms?",
  "response": "Our bodies are made up of **both cells and atoms**, but it's more accurate to say that **cells are built from atoms**. Here's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Atoms:** Atoms are the fundamental building blocks of all matter, including our bodies. Common atoms in the human body include hydrogen, carbon, oxygen, nitrogen, calcium, and phosphorus. These atoms combine to form molecules.\n\n*   **Molecules:** Molecules are formed when two or more atoms bond together. Examples of important molecules in the body are water (H\u2082O), proteins, carbohydrates, lipids (fats), and nucleic acids (DNA and RNA).\n\n*   **Cells:** Cells are the basic structural and functional units of living organisms. They are complex structures made up of various molecules organized in specific ways. Cells contain organelles (like the nucleus, mitochondria, etc.) that perform specialized functions.\n\nSo, while atoms are the most basic level of organization, our body functions as a system of **cells** that are built from molecules, which are in turn built from atoms. Cells are the level at which life's processes truly begin.\n",
